title: Have you ever helped a celebrity without realising who they were? - Quora

response.answer_text: Not quite, but I did once ask a celebrity for help without realizing who they were. I was living in OKC at the time, trying to fix up an old bike, and I needed a part for said bike, so I went on a mission trying to find a bike shop that was actually open on Sundays. I didn't have internet at the time, and I think it was before business hours for most places could be easily brought up on Google anyway, so this involved physically driving to every bike shop I knew of, and checking in person. I'd hit the first three places on my list with no luck, and then went downtown to check out a shop called Bicycle Alley — I don't think it's there anymore, but at the time it was located in a space where you walked in one door for the main building, and there was an indoor corridor that a few other businesses branched off of — kind of like a mall, if malls only had the space for three or four stores in them, and then had offices or apartments on upper floors above them. So the entrance to Bicycle Alley was to the left as soon as you entered this indoor hallway area, and on the right was (and still is, as far as I'm aware) a pretty popular coffee shop called Coffee Slingers. As soon as I walked in the door this little Boston Terrier comes trotting up to me and I was like “oh puppy!” and reached down to pet it, only to hear his person go “no Licorice, come back here,” at which point I kind of half stopped paying attention to the dog and noticed that there were three people sitting in the entryway to Bicycle Alley, drinking their coffee from next door — an older couple and a younger woman in a sundress. I was still mostly hoping to get to pet the doggo though, so I just kind of half-registered this while still looking at the pupper, who apparently belonged to the woman in the sun dress, so I wound up directing my question to her when I asked, “is the bike store here open today by any chance? I've been all over trying to find one that has Sunday hours, and I'm not having much luck so far.” In the process of asking this question, I decided I probably ought to finally take my attention off of the dog and actually look at the person I was talking to… and just as my question/aired frustration is about 2/3rds of the way out of my mouth, I realized who that person was. …And that was how I wound up asking Famke Janssen about the business hours for a local bike shop. Whoops. She gave me a deer-in-headlights look and the kind of exaggerated “I have no fucking clue” type of shrug that you give to someone who asks you something completely unexpected and outside of your realm of expertise, and my jaw probably completely dropped. At that point I just proceeded to stammer and try to redirect my attention to the older couple she was with instead, hoping maybe they were locals at least and might know — they didn't, but got up and tested the doors just to make sure they hadn't accidentally blocked the doorway to an open business, and the doors were, in fact, locked. So I stood there kind of stuttering for a moment more while I debated asking why on earth Famke Janssen was just hanging out having coffee in downtown Oklahoma City (which is definitely NOT the sort of city known for random celebrity sightings, with the occasional exception of members of The Flaming Lips, or NBA players with the OKC Thunder), but ultimately I decided I'd probably butcher her name and embarrass myself further if I tried to say anything more — I'd only seen the name in writing, and hadn't ever heard how it's properly pronounced — and also I realized that they were probably having coffee in this corridor instead of in the actual coffee shop itself, precisely to avoid having random people coming up and asking her lots of questions… so after a few seconds of being indecisive and awkward, I wound up just apologizing for bothering them and wishing them a nice day, and then left. …And I never actually did get to pet the dog.

No. I knew exactly who she was! But no one else around seemed to recognize her. Before the whole COVID19 pandemic; I was working at the MoMA Design Store SoHo in New York, NY. I remember I was opening that day. I was so happy because, instead of working on the main floor like I usually did, I was downstairs in the Kids/Books/HAY section. Everyone at the job knows, that it's a tad bit easier to work down there because some customers don't realize we have a second floor; so they never even visit that section! Alas, it was a slow morning. I was standing by the register when I saw her:  Marion Cotillard. Here she is along side Leonardo Di' Caprio in the movie Inception (one of my favorite films):  She plays his estranged wife Mal, who is seemingly aggressive and combative towards Cobb in most scenes. Here she is in Big Fish (another favorite of mine):  She plays as William Bloom's wife, Josephine Bloom and they're expecting a child. She seems to be the one of the mediators between Will and his father Edward. Her most critically acclaimed role, was her depiction of French singer Édith Piaf, in the movie La Vie en rose and also known as La Môme:  When I first saw her, I knew it was her. I've seen her in many movies but not in person. She looked more like this:   Beautifully, bare-faced, relaxed and down-to-earth. Her eyes are what gave her away to me instantly, then her lips and the small mole on her forehead. I gotta say I was in shock seeing her. I wanted to blabber to her and say that I love her work, so on and so forth…. but I was at work! We exchanged a look and it came to my understanding that she knew, that I knew, who she was. What did I do? I kept my composure and helped her pick out some gifts for her children. She had an assistant with her, who was constantly asking me questions, but Marion was so kind and chill. She didn't have the air of a celebrity at all. She just wanted to shop, be normal, and enjoy her day. I was on the verge of bursting many times, but I thought it was important to respect her as a person first and not make her experience there uncomfortable in anyway. It was lovely meeting her in person. One of the most natural beauties I've seen. I know this question is about meeting a celebrity that I didn't know was one but, I knew who she was and no one else around me did! I think that counts, haha! I felt the same way when I met Lucy Liu one time in an elevator and Alicia Keys when I was getting off from work at another job. But that's for another time, haha. Au Revoir!

response.answer_text: Yeah, actually. Years ago I worked at this huge candy store owed by a heiress (who legit is one of the nicest people I have ever worked for and would love to work for again if she were to ever open a store in my new city) In NYC, and it was very common for all types of people, celebrities included, to come into the store and shop or hold a meeting with her. Usually if a celebrity is coming in for a meeting, the staff would be on notice so we would know to direct them to the cafe where the meetings we’re usually held. This particular day I was not notified that the owner was having a meeting with this celebrity, and he was early so he decided to do some shopping (with his manager) on his own. I happened to be working the fudge counter that day, and I greeted him like any other customer, with a warm smile and asking them if they were interested in a sample. I offered information not only about the fudge we sold, giving my personal recommendations, but I also told him about all the other products we sold in the immediate area of the fudge counter. I kept thinking how handsome he was, but I assumed his manager was actually his wife so I wanted to be respectful and made sure I was including her in the conversation. After I sold him a few pieces of fudge he stepped away to look at what else the store had to offer, and it clicked that his face was very familiar to me. I asked his manager if anyone has ever told her that he looks just like the actor Blair Underwood, and she laughed and said, “Yes, all the time, because that IS Blair Underwood”. I immediately apologized to him for taking up so much of his time, but he was extremely kind and said he was just so impressed that I knew so much about all of the candies and sweets we sold. About an hour or 2 later he came back over to my station with the owner of the store as she was giving him a tour, and and he told her that he was already very familiar with my section, and that me and him go way back. He complimented her on finding the best, most knowledgeable employees and brought 5 more pounds of fudge from me. It was legit the best day of my working life, to have a celebrity talk me up to my boss.

When I worked at Disneyland, we had a lot of celebrities come through. Sometimes they’d get a little special treatment (skip the line, that kind of thing). Well, back in 1999, I was working at the Monorail and they were only running on half the track while California Adventure was being built. It was an ingenious process to keep them running (two trains would run, and the first train into any station would unload and then go just past to wait for the second train to unload and load to return to the original station)- but it meant you had about 20 minutes waiting at any given platform for the two trains to come back. One day, a tour guide came up with a man and a boy and then apologized, but had to go downstairs to talk to someone before they left to go to the Hotel. I did the cursory glance. The guy was tan and thin. He didn’t stand out, so I assumed it was just someone I didn’t know. I was manning the comm, so to speak, and waiting for that first train to come in. The little boy had two of the cap pistols they sold and was shooting everything. He was about 9, and REALLY into it. Being an actress, you can only get shot so many times before you give in to the urge and die a melodramatic death on the platform. “Oh… you got me…” THUD. He giggled, the man laughed. And I got the radio call that the train was coming into the platform. So I apologized and went back to my job. Their guide came up before we let more people up, and I was busy getting people off that first train to pay any more attention to them. I ended up getting on their train (the first one going back to the hotel) to drive. They went in the tailcone with their guide, and the kid shot me one last time. I put my hand over my heart, and muttered “Oh, good shot, kid.” I started to get in while we loaded the rest of the guests on it, and one of the other cast members stopped. “You knew that was Tom Hanks, right?” I did not. And then I had to get into the train, and say a spiel, knowing that Tom Hanks was in the tail cone. (I did, I refrained from making any jokes - and he ended up leaving me a compliment) (As to why I didn’t recognize him - it was during the middle of the break from filming Cast Away. He’d lost a lot of weight for it.)

I was working by myself one slow night at the Subway that I was employed by. Since it was late and slow I had the stereo turned up on the local hard rock station. Two gentlemen came in and placed their order which I got to work on. I couldn't help but overhear the conversation between them and it was about the technical merits of the song playing. You could tell they knew what they were talking about so I casually mentioned that it was obvious that they were in the field of music +fairly common since I live a little outside of Nashville). The one said that yes he has been working in the music business for almost three decades as a musician. My initial thought was a session musician since I didn't recognize him so I asked him if he might have played for anyone I would have heard of. Right away he told me that he is the bass player for the Allman brothers. I told him that while yes I have definitely heard of them I would not consider myself a fan. Not because I disliked them but rather because I was only familiar with the song Midnight Rider. He said that he appreciated the fact that I didn't do like so many people and try to bs him and say I was a big fan. The honesty was refreshing to him. As they were sitting there enjoying the meal I did tell him that my wife was a fan and if it was not a bother could he sign an autograph for her after he finished his meal.After they finished he came to the register and asked if I had a piece of paper and what my wife's name was. After I told him her name was Melissa all he said was “I'll be damned.” Is that your wife's name too? No it's the name of one of our biggest hits. This is the tale of how I ended up becoming friends with Allan Woody and we stayed friends up until he passed away.

Working pretty much any job allows you to run into celebrities. Everybody needs gas, coffee, or a quick roller-grill burrito at two in the morning to fend off the munchies, so it isn’t surprising the know that quite a few famous people spent a lot of their time at a Kinko’s throughout the 1990s. Now, I’ve said elsewhere that “celebrity” is a subjective term. There are people in my world of freaks and geeks that I might drop a baby to rush after in a crowd. But you probably would not know them. Hell, I couldn’t name a single NFL player if you showed me flashcards with half their last name revealed. So, your mileage may vary thinking the people I’ve met working at a copy shop are “real” celebrities. I worked the overnight at a Kinko’s and remember a conversation I had with a guy who came up to the counter to fax something. Me: Hey, you famous? Him: Me? Why? Me: Because the only people who come in here at three in the morning wearing sunglasses and a hoodie are either going to rob the place or don’t want to be identified. I only ask because I want to rule out the first option. Him: Hi, I’m [can’t remember the name he gave] Me: Oh! Cool. [Pretended to know, faxed his papers, went on with my life.] I took an order to make fliers for a member of a rock band. I pointed out the name of their album was spelled wrong on it, so I spent an hour helping him recreate the flier and made prints. That guy was the bassist for the band Fuel, who was on top of one or more Billboard charts less than a year later. I had no idea until the band played locally and I met the guy at the concert. Fun fact: I used the recognition to introduce my date to the guy at the concert thinking it would help my chances of impressing (or just pressing against) her, but she still gave me the dreaded handshake of no-thanks at the end of the evening and later sent me a delightful email telling me she felt nothing when around me except an urgent feeling to not be. I took a custom banner order from a woman who turned out to be a Grammy Award-winner. When I put the face to the music and told her I loved her work, she told me, in so many words, to insert my opinion rectally. For some reason, a number of great comic book artists hit me up for help on my overnight shifts because they were behind schedule and had a flight out in the morning and something was wrong with their work. Most of the work, to me, seemed like portfolio work to present at an interview, but I would later go through my monthly issue of “Previews” and see finished art that looked amazing and very familiar. I THINK, but I can’t be sure, that I once ran into Rob Liefield and asked him why the fuck his characters were so swollen but had no feet. It was either him or another terrible artist with a major landmass for a chest. I think I probably helped people who thought they were celebrities based on how they expected to be treated. Local radio personalities were usually the most self-obsessed jackasses, the “Karens” of that era who would demand satisfaction or the manager’s home phone number to get what they wanted because they were the Kings and Queens of Drive Time in the 25th largest market in the country with their wacky morning zoo shenanigans. fuck I hate those people. They can all be the fifteenth caller and win two tickets to the Land of Shut the Fuck Up. I also mentioned in another post a local activist who later became mayor of my town who wasn’t going to pay in advance as was policy because she believed Jesus would not pay upfront. I didn’t know her at the time but when I saw her empty glare on the news six months later being elected mayor, it was only a matter of time before the nation elected some syphilitic, tangerine twatgoblin to the White House. Oh, and I gave Emo Philips directions to the manager of a comedy club in Philly. I just thought he was a local weirdo looking to buy drugs.

In about 1980, I flew a group of us from Santa Barbara to the Silicon Valley in a Piper Saratoga to try making a software deal up there. I served as both programmer AND pilot… and I owned the flying school / Fixed Base Operator, Norris Airways, at the base of the tower, from which the plane came. The deal didn’t come to much. On the way back, around 6 PM, Santa Barbara went down below IFR minimums of 200 foot decision height and 1/2 mile runway visibility, so light aircraft were stacking up at nearby Santa Ynez airport like so many pancakes on a griddle. Famously at that time, Santa Ynez airport had a fleet of 52 blue 1958 Chevrolet Yeoman rental cars, and they were going fast. The 4 of us got the last one. The airport co-owner and operator, Shy Smith, a longtime friend, ran up to me as I was pulling out of the lot and asked me if I could take someone who’d just landed in a Rockwell 114 and needed to get back to Santa Barbara. I said, Sure, and she said, “Wayne, this is John; John, this is Wayne”. It was John Travolta. He hopped into the car and we headed back the 30 or so miles to Santa Barbara Airport. The other occupants of the car didn’t know who he was, and introduced themselves, and eventually figured it out. It was a very pleasant conversation about airplanes, and he was a really knowledgeable, kind, courteous, and friendly guy. I dropped everyone else off at my flying school, at 1407 Norman Firestone Road. My wife at the time, Maryann, was closing up the school for the day. John was parked at a school on the other side of the field, Apollo Airways. I asked Maryann if she’d mind running John over to Apollo, and she said, Sure. When she returned a few minutes later, I said, “You did know that was John Travolta, right?” She said “NO!! AND WE SHARED A CIGARETTE!” For the record, he’s a very nice person.

I believe that I helped this individual, although he may not feel the same way!! If nothing else, this is a funny story. In the early 90’s my parents were hosting a dinner party at their home. One of the early arrivals was a gentleman that I know I had seen a few times but I just couldn’t place him or remember his name (I was a young guy and didn’t really care about “old people”. It ould have been a different story if this would have been a young lady!). My Dad says to me, “Ellis, you and $#%(unintelligible) have something in common. He teaches at the school that you attended”. This guy then says to me “Nice. What did you think of the school?” Well, he asked!! I proceeded to tell him that I had learned more by my sophomore year in undergrad than I did the entire time getting my MBA at this school. I told him that the majority of my professors were my age and had received their BS, and gone straight on to getting an MBA, and then a PhD. Although they were book-smart, most of these “teachers” had no real-life experience, hence, they could not answer specific questions in anything other than hypothetical textbook fashion! The guy found my answer intriguing and complimented my choice of schools for undergraduate study. In hindsight, he probably also found my answer a bit annoying. He taught a law class and had actually graduated law school before finding his way into his lifelong profession. About twenty minutes after speaking with this gentleman, my Dad tells me that he was surprised, although not shocked, that I would be so blunt and honest with my response to Senator Biden!! Oooops! He truly was a good sport about it, though. Perhaps I helped him realize that you shouldn’t ask questions if you don’t want to hear the truth. LOL! Having met him several times, I can honestly say that he is a genuinely nice person.

This happened in 1977; I was at Lake Tahoe, on the Nevada side; obviously for a weekend fun at the gaming tables; I used to live in the Bay Area of California. I am not a serious gambler; it was only weekend entertainment. I played mostly Black Jack where I had mastered the odds. I was staying at Harrah’s Casino hotel It was late at night when I decided to play a last round before retiring to my room. I sat at the Black Jack table in one end of the table, and to my left on the other end sat a big burly guy dressed in cowboy garb with a cowboy hat on his head; he was visibly intoxicated. Taking another close look at him because he looked familiar, I realized that he was one of the supporting actors you see on TV’s western series; he appeared on Bonanza, Rawhide, and many others. He started making stupid bets dropping big bucks; I watched him lose more than 25,000 Dollars in less than half an hour; I really felt sorry for him. I talked to him, and suggested that he should quit the table and go to sleep it off. He said no; I am sober and in full control, so I wished good night and went to sleep. A week later; I was at the San Francisco airport boarding a PanAm flight to London. I stood in the check-in line for my flight; right behind me there was the same big burly cowboy; I turned around and spoke to him; I said: you look familiar, I have seen you not long ago; he said: I am sure you have seen me in this movie, or that movie or that TV show. I looked at him and said: No; I have seen you at Harrah’s in Lake Tahoe dropping lots of cash at the Black Jack table, his composure turned immediately grim, and said: Oh don’t remind me; and why didn’t you stop me?; I said: I have tried but you would have none of it. We boarded the plane and went our separate ways.

Good golly Miss Dolly In 1986 I owned and operated my own small trucking company and had the rig leased to Suwanee Transportation in Orlando, Fl. It was about that time I started hauling P.V.C. Pipe from Adel Georgia to Pigeon Forge Tennessee for a new project called Dollywood. Two loads each week for three months and they paid really good so I got every load I could possibly get, Inside the construction gate there was a small office where you checked in each delivery with the secretary, A pretty little thing with the most delicious syrupy Southern accent named Katie. Katie and I became fast friends and She always ask me if I would like to have some coffee and a sweet roll every time I came in that little office, There was a break room on the back side of the office and She made a urn of coffee every morning and seeing as how you couldn't drive inside until the workers had their morning safety meeting I drank many cups of coffee back yonder. One morning I was sitting in the break room staring as the world outside became visible as the Sun came peeking over the mountains, I heard someone behind me getting a cup from the cupboard and thinking it was Katie never paid any attention to it, Then someone puled a chair out from the table where I was sitting and I turned to speak to Katie but it wasn't Her, There beside me was the one and only Dolly Parton IN PERSON !!!, She was as pretty as a picture and I suddenly lost my voice, I looked back out the window and as I did so Dolly said "Howdy Mr. Trucker, Cat got your tongue?". I was still in shock at seeing Her and managed a mumbled "No Ma'am", Dolly laughed and said "It's all right I don't bite" and I grinned at Her and said " No Ma'am I reckon you don't". I slowly got over my shyness and began to become comfortable with the idea of sitting next to a real Country Legend and pretty soon it was like we were old friends so I says to Her " You know you messed up naming this place Dollywood don't ya ?" , With a quizzical look Dolly says "What would you have named it ?", I replied "Hooterville" This warm gracious lady laughed with REAL laughter at what I had said and Yelled at Kaite up front "Hey Katie I'm changing the name to Hootersville", Katie came walking to the back with a paper towell over Her face and Said "Dammit Dolly you made coffee spurt out my nose". I made many deliveries to Dollywood but never did get another chance to visit with Dolly again.

I didn’t help him, but he ended up helping me and I had no idea that he was someone famous at the time. This was probably 2000 and I was traveling to Seattle for a work trip. I handled marketing for a Fortune 500 company at the time and the last event that I was in charge of, some of my materials didn’t make it to the location on time. As a result, I decided that this trip, I would bring a suitcase solely dedicated to brochures, pamphlets etc to ensure that I had what I needed. As I was leaving the airport and taking the escalator from baggage claim, the suitcase tipped over from the heavy weight, causing a train wreck behind me. I was a little frazzled and embarrassed, trying to get everything situated so I could move out of everyone’s way. The man behind me was super nice, helping me with the suitcase. Not only did he wheel my suitcase(s) to the rental car shuttle, he also loaded it for me. I thanked him and went on my way. I went to the hotel to check in and coincidentally ran into him again at the front desk again. I teased him, asking him if he was following me. He grinned and we laughed together. He wished me goodbye and went to his room. The hotel clerk asked me how I knew Mr. Cameron. I told him that I didn’t know who he was talking about. He then informed me that the nice man who helped me was Professional Major League Baseball Outfielder Mike Cameron Mike Cameron - Wikipedia. He had just left the Cincinnati Reds to go to the Seattle Mariners at the time.

I don’t know if I helped her or not but it is a funny story. I went to Tokyo for work on first class from LA to Tokyo because I was invited by the government of Japan (no, I don’t have that kind of money to spend on a flight!) Anyway, as soon as I sat down, surrounded by mostly other people dressed like me (businessish casual attires), this Japanese girl sat next to me. She was in her early 20s but who dressed like a teenager taken out of a funky magazine (ripped jeans, lots of jewelry, makeup, etc). We chatted for a while and got my attention that her English was really good on a casual way, meaning that it was not the usual academic English I am used to hear from governement officials. She told me she lived in Japan but that she spends a lot of time in the US and not wanting to be intrusive, I didn’t ask her what she did for living and she didn’t offer either. I sensed she felt very comfortable not talking about herself overall. Finally, when we landed in Tokyo, she gave me a big hug, which is very uncommon among Japanese people, and we said goodbye. I went through the usual customs ritual for foreigners and by the time I reached the gates to the exit, I found my new friend in front of a wall of reporters and photographers and she was answering questions. As I walked by with my luggage, she saw me out of the corner of her eye, she turned around, yelled my name, left the press area and gave me another hug. I was so puzzled and shocked to see that she was some sort of celebrity that I just said goodbye and kept going… only to be followed by a sea of reporters and photographers who started asking me all kinds of questions, mostly in Japanese! and all I said, “I don’t speak Japanese and I only met her on the flight”. I don’t think any of the reporters understood what I said anyway and as soon as I spotted the driver with my name on a board, I ran to him and jumped into the car… it looked like the movies where the reporters kept banging the windows of the car and taking photos. That was the end of it… and to this day I don’t even know who she was!

Haha yes and it was hilarious. I was in a hotel, having run from the swimming pool back to my room to get something. I was in my bathing suit, no glasses or contact lenses. I’m nearsighted; I can’t recognize people much more than 15 feet away; within 10 feet I do well. As I’m getting on, I see a couple pushing a baby carriage trying to get to the elevator. I held the door for them and they got in. Nothing out of the ordinary, just basic politeness. They seemed nice, but the woman was distraught that her baby was crying. I told her not to worry, I have a baby, I get it, and you have a beautiful kid there. I could tell a wave of relief came over both of them. They seemed truly encouraged to hear someone say this. I thought that a touch odd; again, just normal politeness. We went down the elevator together and said polite things and smiled at each other as we got out of the elevator. Total time from first seeing them to saying have a nice day was less than 2 minutes. I thought they were just a couple of nice, wealthy, stressed out parents. NBD. The hotel was full of people like that. I then saw my friends in the lobby, waiting for me. They had a kind of astonished look on their faces. I asked what was going on; at first, they wouldn’t say anything. Then one asked if I had any idea who I was talking to; I looked and realized it was John Travolta and Kelly Preston! They wanted me to go over and get an autograph or just say something but I felt it would have ruined the moment for them; they probably more than anything appreciated not being recognized and hassled.

Yeah. I worked at a diner in West Hollywood that frequently had directors and ppl like that come in, but rarely actors. I'm not terribly start struck anyway, so I didn't really pay attention. One man came in and I served him as my normal chipper little self, as I did anyone- cuz no one else wanted to. He was there in cut-offs and a T-shirt and sandals, and not of the expensive kind, and a baseball cap. Nothing he wore said, "I'm trying to hide who I really am", so no one looked, and it was busy. ok, so anyway- I'm talkative and cheerful to everyone, and I was with him, and the lunch rush passed and my fellow waitstaff started paying more attention to stuff and someone told me the guy I was serving was some guy from a sitcom (I can't remember anything about it but that it was a Brady bunch kinda theme with an x-blonde hombshell as the mom and this particular guy was that bum friend who frequently visited that lived in his van). I'd never seen the show and didn't really care, but as the crowd died, there were looks his direction and a few giggles, and life went on. When he left, he came up to me personally, to pay the bill, and gave me an $80 tip (on a $30 check). He took my hand and smiled, "thanks for being normal", and left. Someone actually did snap a pic of him as he was getting out to the parking lot lol.

If I did then I still don’t know it! I did work at the Longboat Key Club for a while in different departments and celebrities frequented the hotel there. Unfortunately, I only had one “experience” with a celebrity and I knew very well who they were. All staff at the hotel, and entire property for that matter, know the rules for dealing with celebrities…you don’t engage them to ask for autographs or ANYTHING while they are there. They are NORMAL GUESTS and are to be treated exactly the same way as any other guests on property. Some of the celebrities have used aliases and even if you KNOW, for example, that the person you are waiting on is Robert DeNiro, you never ever would call him that if he is going by “Mr. Smith” while there. (note: I don’t know if that is an actual alias that Mr. DeNiro uses or if he even stays there…it was just made up as an example). That is grounds for firing and all the employees know it very well…as do the celebrities. They enjoy their anonymity and that’s one of the reasons they frequent that place. In my case, I was working in the graphics office and we were asked to help out at the hotel with some of the Easter festivities one day. I was tasked with taking Polaroid photos of the guests and their families with the Easter Bunny. There were a ton of kids and I spent a good couple of hours there interacting and taking photos. It was a fun day. As I turned to the next guests in line I paused for a second as Joe Perry, the lead guitarist for Aerosmith walked up with his wife and kids. I just smiled and told them they were welcome to gather around and I’ll take the picture for them, which I did. I handed him the photo and said, “Thank you, sir. I hope you and your family have a wonderful day!” He smiled and said thanks back to me and then went along with his family. Very simple interaction but it made my day! :-) He and his family were very nice and friendly.

In 1988 I was a student working part time in a bank during the Calgary Winter Olympics. People in Calgary were jacked up. The events, the world attention, venues all over the south half of the province. I was working for a few days in a branch that was about halfway between the Olympic Saddledome (hockey, figure skating) and Canada Olympic Park (freestyle skiing, luge, bobsled, ski jumping.) Everyone’s second favourite activity was looking out for world class athletes, media stars from the big networks, a handful of Hollywood celebrities. And it seemed like everyone had a story or at least a sighting, except me. Because I was busy earning money instead of spending it on Olympic priced tickets. Customer service during that time was mostly exchanging US and Japanese currency and cashing traveler’s cheques. Going in for a break just after serving a busy line up of tourists, the staff was buzzing about Mary Hart being in the branch, long time host of Entertainment Tonight (and former Miss South Dakota, I looked that up.) That’s as A-list as it gets and one of the most famous faces on TV. I was kicking myself for being too busy with customers to not get a glimpse. And then someone told me that I was the one who served her. Depending on the transaction, I probably even checked her ID. Yep. Nice ID work, Jeff. I did remember her after the fact, since she had only left a few minutes previous, not as Mary Hart but as a very friendly and charming American in a nice coat with great hair. Oh well. Pretty sure she didn’t recognize me either. I found this picture from Ski Magazine (photo Peter Borsari,) not the Olympics but a nearby event in Banff a few months later the same year:

Yes. Was at a big music trade show…..and we ended up working most of the week together - practically side by side. (we were endorsing artists for two different manufacturers at the time, at the companies expense - just helping out and repping them as Artists. ) On this day we were watching everyone set up for the show and he had to run to his car for some boxes of stuff. I simply asked if he needed any help - he said “Sure” but then told me that the rental car he was driving was parked about 3/4 mile away. Even though it was a bit of a walk, I still helped out. Truth be told, I really just wanted to get some fresh air and get out of the convention center that I’d been in for several hours. (stuffy and boring) Turns out - he was parked in the same hotel parking lot that I was booked at and we then realized that we both had rooms in the same hotel. Later that night on the way back to the hotel we decided to grab a bite to eat in the hotel restaurant and just kicked back and chilaxed. As I said….we worked all week within 10 feet of each other at the show and ended up laughing it up during all of it and became pretty good friends. Turns out he was a pretty popular drummer in a heavy rock band - but I never recognized him because he wasn’t all “hair’d out”, He simply had a pony tail and was dressed like a normal guy. We’ve maintained our friendship over the years and are still good friends. I’ve visited him with my fam, met his, and he’s really a terrific guy. Sorry……not gonna tell you who it is.

I’ve written this before, but this prompt is more fitting: I’m not much of a sports fan. I love tennis, and I quite enjoy going to a stadium to watch the Dodgers play. Other than that, I do not know much about much (that’s fairly accurate even outside of sports). Okay, preface done. My first job outside of tennis was at a Big 5 Sporting Goods. Just a general sports store with good deals on select items on a constantly rotating schedule. That is, do not buy anything unless it is on sale. The markup on non-sales item is ridiculous . . .Sorry, another tangent. My store location was in Ranch Bernardo, San Diego. My main job was to roam the tennis section, weights, and shoes. My coworkers called in sick a lot, so the floor was understaffed with my manager at the gun rack and me between the cash register and the shoes in the back. Fortunately it was slow. I was on my thirtieth minute haggling with an 80 year old about her foot size. She insisted her foot was two sizes smaller than they were. A very athletic man walked in, and I took the opportunity to let the 80 year old mature. The man beelined to the footballs, and he joked with me a bit about needing one in the first place. I told him about each product; information I had read about in the pamphlets, having no real knowledge. He asked what I looked for in a football. I confessed I was the wrong guy to ask, and joked that they should be less round than a basketball. At that, I helped him carry 5 balls to the register and checked him out. After tending to the 80 year old — I put size 8s into a size 6 box because those were the best fit — my manager asked how my conversation went with the man. “Fine. I sold him 5 balls.” “You sold footballs to him?” “Yep.” My manager gave me several seconds for something to click. Nothing. He grew impatient. “You sold footballs to LT! You sold footballs to LaDainian Tomlinson. Dude, you really need to get out more.”  So, sure. I am ignorant. But I just treated him like a normal person, which, he is, and deserves the opportunity to be treated as such. LaDainian Tomlinson - Wikipedia

I travel a lot on business, always out of San Francisco International Airport (SFO), so I know the terminal layout like the back of my hand. One day, leaving for a business trip, I get through TSA and turn left to head toward my gate. There’s a couple behind me, heading in the same direction. She turns to him and says, “Let’s move fast. I’m busting for a pee!” I turn around and tell her, “If you need a toilet immediately, don’t come this way. Turn right, and there’s a Ladies about 20 feet down on your right. The nearest one this way is a 6–8 minute walk.” She calls “Thanks!” over her shoulder as she runs for the nearer loo. Her (husband? boyfriend?) turns to me and thanks me, and apologizes if they’ve held me up. I say, “No problem”, and look up at his face (for the first time). “Oh my god! Rob Lowe!” He chuckled and said he figured I had helped him because he’s who he is. “Nope. I’d have done the same for any fellow traveler. SFO is laid out oddly.” And, of course, I said (I’m SUCH a geek!): “So, I’m curious . . .How many Lowe’s could Rob Lowe rob if Rob Lowe could rob Lowe’s?” He asked me to repeat it, chuckled, stood waiting for his (wife/girlfriend?), and I headed off to my gate. Ships, people. Ships.

Back in 2010, I was working as “back stage” tech for the Oprah “show”. I was in charge of managing and monitoring nearly everything backstage - because I’m a Yank. I actually spent more than a week building the stage (58 tonnes!), too - which was quite fun. I was rather angry that I go re-assigned to do this role. Either which, the “Green Room” - which is where celebs get refreshed and eat and drink - was one of my primary jobs. I always made sure everything was pristine and in order. One day, a few days into the gig, I walked in after having a smoko, and this woman was re-organising everything, cleaning up and re-arranging furniture! WTF! She was in a lovely dress, was smiling, and I just couldn’t believe what I was seeing. I had to ask her to stop or else I’d call security (we had radios). She looked at me and asked me to give her a hand moving a table. Which I did. Cuz I’m a nice bloke and don’t want to argue with women. She started to ask about what I do (did), where I was from, about my parents and family, obviously what my name was, am I being treated well, am I enjoying “Oprah at the Opera House”, do I miss the US, do I like Sydney, what foods do I like… And then I said, “Sorry Ma’am, but I do have to ask your name because I have to get back to the stage…” - Olivia. She gave me a huge hug and I went back to work. It did NOT dawn on me that it was Olivia Newton-John until I had to escort her to the stage. FARKINHELL. She also called me over to her limo to give me another hug before she left. WTF. What a lovely human being! Peace and blessings. (Have met more, but Olivia is my absolute fave)

It wasn’t me, but a good friend of mine. She was out shopping with another friend at an expensive department store, in San Francisco. While her friend was trying on some clothes she had wandered over to the jewelry counter to look while she waited. A very nice man asked her if she could help him decide on a diamond ring for his wife. She said that he had this huge ostentatious diamond surrounded with clusters of diamonds that just looked garish. They walked over to the rings and she helped him pick out a very tasteful 1.5 carat in a beautiful setting. He was so happy he gave her a hug and kiss on the cheek. I am surprised that she didn’t slap him, because that was her personality. She had noticed her friend come out of the changing room and she kept waving at her and motioning her to come over, my friend said she made her wait because she was helping the nice man. After he and she said goodbye and parted her friend came rushing over to her loudly asking, “Do you know who that was?” She was very excited and my friend of course replied no, and her friend burst out even louder, “That was Joe Montana!” This was during the time the 49’ers were on top. My friend looked at her friend and asked, “who’s he?”. She was clueless, never having watched football.

I had finished my shift at work, took off my lab coat and hung it up. I put on my blazer that I had just acquired from a consignment shop. I have always shopped secondhand stores since I can remember. I have probably spent way too much time combing through Goodwill and various resale shops. I gathered my purse and headed through the lobby to the elevators that eventually would take me to the parking lot. On the way through the lobby I got flagged down by a woman who was sitting with a small group of people. Now, I have never been interested in celebrities, and I rarely go to the movies. So, the following scenario is hardly farfetched. The lady admired my jacket and wanted to know where I got it. I have no shame in buying secondhand and I gladly gave her the name of the consignment store. As we all know there are usually only one of a kinds in these type of stores, but there were actually two of these since they were sent as merchandise that the retail store was most likely unable to sell (it really was cute). I thought nothing of it and went on with the rest of what was left of the day. Eventually I returned to the store to scope out the goods. The owner approached me and thanked me for sending Jamie Lee Curtis into the store to buy the blazer, which in fact, she did. I helped Jamie Lee Curtis with her wardrobe, which I have heard that some celebrities actually pay people to do.

I use to work at a 24/7 restaurant that was next to a hip-hop/rap type club. Some rapper made it a popular spot because he always ate there after shows. Apparently I've served quite a few. I still really have no clue who they were. A few rappers, a basketball player from Houstons team, and one of the dudes from a 70/80s rock band. I couldnt quite put my finger on it, but I so reconized him. They were all respectful. Rocker dude reminded me of a biker, he was super cool, he even initiated conversation with me… His wife, I assume, was beautiful. She had this amazing dirty blond curly hair, the kind us curly headed people only wish we had. I was surprised the basketball player was alone. That time of night people came in from partying, concerts and such, almost always a group. Was quiet too, really kept to himself, kept head down most the time, maybe just tired. Hope it wasnt a bad night. I didnt pay much attention to the rappers, they had loud, energetic groups, but I did laugh at myself for expecting to see them like they look in the videos I have seen. Only one was actually dressed with all the chains and such in excess. The women though, wow… It was cool, almost like watching a fashion show. The dresses were so neat, coolest shoes I have EVER seen, make up, jewelry, hair, nails, it was all so pretty. I could spend hours just watching it all. The cars blew me away. One world I could not ever fit into, or really want to try, but I sure enjoyed watching it.

I worked as a ticket agent in my home town airport. Back before 9/11 we were a little looser with accepting tickets from other airlines and whatnot, and a supervisor had shown me how to use ticket changes to our advantage. So, when someone would come up with a full fare ticket from another airline, I’d accept it because we’d get a decent chunk of that. Those cheap, non refundable one way type tickets were virtually worthless unless we had plenty of open seats. Anyway, one sleepy Sunday afternoon I’m manning the ticket counter. Up walks a fairly tall foreign sounding guy and, hands me his ticket (from another airline) and asked me if he could use that to get an earlier flight on my airline. I didn’t even look at the name, just checked the ticket fare and started to look for an earlier flight. As I’m typing away my phone rings and I answer it. It’s a buddy at another airline a few counters away. He says “Hey, that’s Boris Becker.” So I said “What!?” Then, without hanging up I look at the name on the ticket, then I look up at the gentleman in front of me and ask (like an idiot) “Are you BORIS BECKER?” He just said yes, I said neat, told my friend he was right and hung up. So, his ticket really wasn’t worth that much, but it was a slow day so I was going to help him out anyway. Finding out who he was just made my day, mostly because my mom was going to freak out (she was a huge fan). I took the ticket and got him out about an hour earlier.

One day at the boutique I worked at a short, older guy came in wearing all black rocking a dope leather jacket and tortoise shell aviators with blue tinted lenses. Super chill demeanor. He had the coolest jewelry on, all these different custom pieces. I love gems and crystals so I complimented him and he started telling the different stories about all of the places around the world he got them from. He then tells me he’s from Chicago like me but grew up in a rougher neighborhood. I was like okay “this dudes seem some shit.” He had amazing taste and picked out all of the new pieces that I loved: denim, reversible bomber, cashmere sweaters. After spending quite a bit of cash, he came back later and spent more. I looked him up after getting his information for an alteration, his name is Chuck Panozzo. When he comes back to pick up his stuff I admit guiltily that I googled him. He’s the bass player for the band Styx! He was so humble and told all these awesome stories yet conveniently left out that little fact. After chatting some more, he gives me a mother of pearl guitar pic with the band logo on it as a thank you. I asked him if he’s used it to play before and he said yeah. My little brother is a guitar player so I like to remind him of this story now and again. Of course I still have the pic!

Just a minor story but one I’ll never forget. it was Mother’s Day. I was working as a chauffeur. While working for a major airline at Washington National Airport (DCA) my crew and I were unloading an aircraft. When a bag came out, I noticed a gold chain hanging out from a slightly open zipper. I finally found out through co-workers who she was and it never weighed in regarding our friendship. All I can say is the world is a lesser place without Ms Angelos’s presence. I’m very blessed to have had this small but meaningful relationship with her! I can still hear her unique voice…

Yes. Lots. But more like “help” as in, “Do you want a window seat or aisle?” In college, I worked in an airline lounge for frequent flyers and VIP guests. Celebrities were a common thing. But there was one problem. I was among the micro-percentage of American kids who grew up without a TV. Important people – whether by fame or fortune - just didn’t appear on my radar of things to care about. Maybe that’s why they let me work there. I could help famous people and treat them normally because I had no idea who these people were to begin with. Famous people finally got their wish of “being treated like everyone else.” Conversations with my colleagues often sounded like this: Colleague: “You know who that was, right?” Me: “Who?” Colleague: “That guy you just helped. That’s Burt Reynolds” Me: “Which guy? I just helped three people.” Colleague: “Ugh, never mind.” So I didn’t. And this repeated itself. They’d tell me who it was, and I’d think, “that’s cool.” and carry on with checking the weather - because that’s what you do when you work at an airport. But there were a few celebrities who stood out to me. I remember John Goodman being really laid back and polite. Quiet. He’d actually take his empty water glass back to the bar when finished.  My favorite celebrity was Isaac Hayes (RIP man). He’d come in and talk to us like old friends. One time my colleague and I got him to sing to us in an empty lounge. His voice boomed. And it was awesome. He was awesome.  50 Cent was a really cool guy, too. Super chill. I had to focus on not calling him 50 Cents because I wasn’t used to saying his name and my brain wanted to use the plural form of ‘cent’ since we were talking about more than one penny.  But I’ll never forget the time when Burt Reynolds was saying goodbye. As he was leaving, my colleague just couldn’t help herself. “Mr. Reynolds. I have to say. I’m crazy about you.” He paused, looked her dead in the eye, and said: “I’m crazy about you, too.” He left. She melted. Her life was complete. So the next time someone says they’re crazy about you, instead of calling the police, you know what to say instead.

Here’s one for all you oldies out there. I live in NYC, and I was working for RCA at the time, which was the parent company of NBC back then. They had an Exhibition hall across from 30 Rock where they had a sort of Museum about the RCA company. They also had one very drunk celebrity there one afternoon. It was maybe 2 pm, and I was bringing something over to the Exhibition Hall for one of the RCA executives. I opened the door and there was this guy being held up on both sides by a gorgeous blonde and a brunette. He was totally incoherent and could not stand on his own two feet, not even close, that’s about as drunk as I have ever seen anyone. Another guy who was off to the side asked me to please hold the door so they could get him out. As I am holding the door and they are walking him out in front of me, I realized that it was Buddy Hackett. He was due to appear on the Tonight show, which taped at NBC across the street in the early evening, maybe about 6 pm if memory serves. There was no way he was going to keep that date! That night I decided to watch the Tonight Show, fully expecting to hear the disclaimer about Hackett not being on the show and to see what excuse they would give. He was on the show! I was shocked! Now, he might have had a slight speech impediment because he was never a very clear speaker, his voice always struck me as odd. If you look for him on Youtube you’ll see what I mean. However, he pulled it off, managing to sober up enough to seem reasonable in 3–4 hours. I thought for sure he would be incoherent for days, but I guess he was just used to being that drunk and recovered quickly, not sounding much different than he always did.

Mmmmm, in a way I suppose? More not realising that part of their lost luggage belonged to a celebrity. I was working in the customs hall and cannot bear mess. I have to find a home or an owner for everything. Under the stairs next to our desk (Pan Am) was a box which had been ripped open and just left? No name, no tag, absolutely nothing to identify the owner. The contents pouring out were some type of cassette ‘similar’ to a video cassette from the old days, but different? Black and an entire box full. I could only log it and wait to see if perhaps another airport were searching for it over the following days. I was driving home singing along to the radio as usual when an announcement that Stevie Wonder had lost some valuable equipment and without it he had had a wasted journey to the U.K. I telephoned the radio station when I got home, told them about the box and it’s whereabouts and thought no more. A few days later a box arrived for ME with a thank you, it was full of Stevie Wonder LP’s, Vinyl as now known! So must have been the one and they contacted the airline that brought him to the U.K. to forward it to him! Lovely gesture, thank you so much!

I sell handcrafted jewelry at my local farmer’s and craft market. Where I live, our winters aren’t too bad, so this outdoor market is year round. One day, a woman came into my booth, looking at bracelets that I was making at the time. She was more elegant than our regular visitors, had long, blond hair and was wearing a fur coat I think. She purchased a bracelet and asked if she could contact me later if she wanted to order more. She apparently visits my small city occasionally, but lives in Los Angeles. I gave her my business card. She told me her name was Loretta. Later that week, I received a call from Loretta. We discussed her order for another bracelet and before we finished she gave me her full name- Loretta Swit. I replied, “Oh just like the actress!” No, duh. She replied, “I am the actress.” I felt pretty stupid. I remember that I had noticed a certain elegance about her, but just figured she was someone with money. I seriously did not recognize her that day when she was in my booth. The thing is, I think Loretta Swit has a distinctive voice, yet even when speaking with her in person, I did not make the connection.

This didn’t happen to me, but via one of my best friend’s daughters. It is one of my all-time favorite stories: Sara (my friend’s daughter) has a best friend named Becky. Years ago, Becky was dating a young man, in his 20’s, who was hard at work building his own landscape business in Ventura County, California. He had a job up at one of the big, beautiful estates in Montecito near Santa Barbara. One morning he was working at the front of the estate, when a (handsome—the obvious identifier) young, friendly man approached him, and began asking about plants and landscape. After awhile the handsome guy asked the landscape guy if they could have lunch together and continue their conversation. Hoping to get a new commission the landscape guy agreed. Handsome guy hesitated, “Maybe it would be better if you picked us up something so we won’t be disturbed.” Landscape guy was confused. Handsome guy says, “You don’t know who I am?” Landscape guy shakes his head, “No.” “I’m Brad Pitt.” Landscape guy replies, “Sorry. I don’t watch much TV.” This was when Brad Pitt and Jennifer Aniston were married. Landscape guy got the job.

Back in the seventies, this groupie was outside The Warehouse in New Orleans following a Joe Cocker concert. I was being interviewed for his film “Mad Dogs and Englishmen”, but my responses were too raunchy and I ended up on the cutting room floor. Boo Hoo! I, then set my sights on getting on Joe’s bus, which I did, by promising to get him and Leon Russell high with some good opium laced hashish I had on me. The dude who was guarding the entrance to the bus that night and had to firsthand check my stuff was in dire need of getting stoned himself and so we huddled together and smoked on a bowl before going up the stairs inside. It only took a couple hits and he was feeling it and knew I was ok to join the party. Booze was flowing and my dope was passed around to the upper echelon. Now that included the door guard. We were all getting royally shit-faced and having a fanfuckingtastic time. I staggered over to my friend, who got me in. “Hey Luv thanks for the high. I really needed it. Seems they like it too,” he laughed tilting his head in the group’s direction. “Yeah, Baby seems to have scored you some points. Got you outta doorman detail and hobnobbing with the biggies.” He looked perplexed, but smiled. “I have to run,” I said kissing him sweetly on the lips, “It’s been real. By the way, Babe. What’s your name?” “Stevie. Stevie Winwood.”

One Christmas I got a call from a woman with an upper-class British accent. Her 8-year-old nephew stuttered and his speech clinic, at their local university, used a delayed auditory feedback (DAF) device made by my company. Her nephew could only go to therapy once a week so the SLP recommended that the family buy a device to use at home every day. She wanted the device shipped to Miami, where she was on vacation. We talked about the boy’s therapy and his speech for 45 minutes. I have these conversations every day. I had the invoice and shipping label finished, addressed to Alia Al-Hussein, in Miami. I didn’t recognize the name. Finally I had to charge her American Express card, which requires entering the address the credit bills go to. She didn’t want to give me the address. I said that it only needed the numbers in the street address and the postal code. She said that her home didn’t have a street address or a postal code, and that it was in a foreign country. I said that the bank might not allow a charge from a foreign country without the billing address. She said, “Royal Palace, Amman, Jordan.” Oh, Princess Alia! She said yes. I charged the credit card. Then I asked her for a favor. A customer in Bethlehem had bought a device, I’d shipped it, but Israel refused to deliver the package. Is there anything she could do? Princess Alia told me to ship the two devices to her, and she would have the package sent to her embassy in Tel Aviv, and my customer could pick it up there. What struck me was her tone in the conversation. It was like, “I’m a princess. Serving my subjects is my job. This is what I do every day.” That’s a real princess.

I once helped Celine Dion connect to hotel Wi-Fi. Celine toured South Africa in 2008 (I think?). I was employed at a Wi-Fi hotspot operator at the time. One day I had to go to The Palazzo Montecasino for routine maintenance on some equipment when our on-site techie told me there are problems on the 6th floor. The 6th floor is actually just one suite, I believe they called it the Presidential Suite, and Celine was staying there. Evidently she had issues connecting to the Wi-Fi. I accompanied the on-site techie (very much a junior employee) to the suite to ensure everything was in order. Celine’s husband opened the door when we knocked and explained that the Wi-Fi signal was visible, but no internet breakout was possible when connecting to it. I diagnosed the issue in less than 3 minutes (a dead CPE caused the Wi-Fi AP to broadcast, but not connect back to the gateway) and replaced the offending piece of equipment. Celine’s husband tipped each of us $100 US which was a lot of money, considering this is South Africa! Only when we left the room did the security escort ask us if we knew who stayed in the room, we both had no idea who the generous foreigner was…

I won’t lie to you, although they were amongst the most famous on the planet, I had no idea who those people were and wouldn’t recognise them today. A Scottish guy whom I once shared a flat with called me up. I had not spoken to him in years. Something had happened but neither of remembered what it was. Anyway, he knew I trained as a teacher. And he had a cousin who was a teacher. Right. Now she was ‘all knocked up and so’. Right. If I was looking for a job? I told him I’d rather have an eye removed than teaching in Scotland. He told me he’d fix that for me, but the job was in India. Posh private school, good pay. Right. I didn’t like the work I was doing - office work that kept me afloat. With little ado I set off with a four month contract, extendable to eight. I’d have my room on the campus and a reasonable wage. (that turned out to be a bummer, but little I cared then). What I thought was going to be a walk in the park turned out to be a blindfolded trip in a burning jungle. The kids were super prepared. The staff was mega serious. My colleagues didn’t sweat, joked in Latin, gossiped in Hindi, taught effortless and controlled their classes by mere staring severely. They lived in real houses. They had family. They had an actual social life. It was clear I was under-qualified and studied constantly. I got books from the school library and read them in the shade of the trees lining the cricket field, or on a bench under the enormous fan in the ‘lounge’. When the director passed he’d slow down, observe me and walk on without saying a word. The time I could hold my breath. That man scared me. The kids had loved their Scottish teacher. And they didn’t like me. ‘Mrs. Gillmore let us use the dictionary’ or ‘Mrs. Gillmore knew our names, our real names’. I had given them made up names. After about a month and a half I got used to the climate. My sweating was under control and learned to appreciate the food. The word went round I was a studious kind of person. Which I from then on enhanced by always carrying a book around. Time flew by and I was even invited to some of the parties my colleagues threw now and then. But let’s get to the famous people now. I must have met a bunch of them when we had ‘evaluation day’. Parents came over to talk to teachers. Although my subject was far from important, many booked an appointment. That freaked me out since I did not remember the student’s names. I opted for the a variation on the ‘I note a clear and steady progress ’ theme. Movie stars, politician and sports people sat down in front of me. I had no idea who they were. It may sound silly. But I had never been to India before, the only Indian film I’d seen was ‘Salaam Bombay’ and I wasn’t into sports. It was clear these people had class, money, experience. I just didn’t know them. It charmed some and upset others. One of these others sat on the school board and would vote against my contract extension. One day the director himself came knocking on my door. He hated to ask me this but I had to do him a favour. A group of journalists and fans had gathered in front of the main entrance of the school. They had followed an actress on her way to the airport. It got rowdy and she pulled in the guarded school parking. Now I had to drive out while she hid under a blanket. Before I could tell them I had not driven a a car in years I was already sitting behind the steering wheel of a far too powerful vehicle. Reporters stormed the car and some even made pictures, although they were clearly disappointed by my appearance. After driving for ten minutes or see the actress crawled from under the blanket, drowning in sweat. We made it to the VIP parking of the airport. Her make up a disaster. She’d take care of that. There were wipes in the glove compartment, no worries. As I was getting out of the car she told me to take care. And then she said ‘call me sometimes Ian’. She knew my name! I didn’t know her name though and couldn’t recognise her in the magazines. Thanks to the blurred make up. I considered asking the director but he scared me. I had trouble breathing when he was around. ‘Who was that woman you told me to escort’? was simply too much. She never showed up, not in real life anyway. I did meet mrs. Gillmore years later in Berlin, in a beer garden. She never went back to teach and regretted it. I am not sure she blamed the kid who was pulling her skirt. It surely felt that way. She promised to say hello to Ginger McThief.

Not me, but my mother did once. She was in a supermarket and was walking down one of the produce aisles. A kind man walked up to her, and said he had no idea what a specific type of fruit looked like. I can’t remember the name, but I’m sure it was some weird exotic one. My mother gladly agreed to help the man and quickly found the item he was looking for, and even stayed to chat with him for a bit. When the two made it to the check-out line, the cashier, who was checking out the old man, began to freak out. She asked many questions that confused my mother such as: “Wait, is it really you?””Do you think I could take a picture with you?””I have a poster from one of your movies.” That’s when my mother got a good look at the man. It was Clint Eastwood, and if it weren’t for the woman at the register, she would’ve never realized she’d just helped a movie icon find a simple piece of fruit. It isn’t my experience, but it’s one of my favorite stories my mother’s ever told.

We spent quite awhile trying things on and discussing what he needed. He was incredibly nice and very easy to work with in general. At the end, just before he went to get his boots paid for, he asks me if I like ice cream. I was a little confused but told him that yes, I do like ice cream. He then reaches into his bag and pulls out a stack of coupons for free Ben and Jerry’s ice cream and hands them to me. The girl standing next to me blurts out “well, who do you think you are, Ben?” He glances over at her and says “no, I’m Jerry.”

Yes. About 3 or 4 years ago, on a brusque windy late winter day in New York, I was leaving the Time Warner Center in Manhattan. As I was going out, a woman all bundled up against the high winds carrying several bags and packages was headed my way toward the door I was exiting through. She wasn't that close, but since she had her hands full and it was cold and I wasn't in a rush anyway, I held the door for her. She started walking faster and I said, “don’t rush, take your time.” Once inside she smiled at me and said, “thank you so much,” while removing her hat and hood - and that's when I saw…it was Gayle King. (I said, ''you're welcome,” and we went our opposite ways.) So yes, I did help a celebrity without realizing who they were, but I wasn't expecting this woman to be a celebrity. I would hold the door for anyone.

Family and I where at the airport in Vienna Austria and we needed someone to take a foto of us. I went to the first guy next to us with the camera. As the guy was taking the camera/smartphone I remember he reacted kind of amused. It was this guy:  Klaas Heufer-Umlauf. He is very well known in Germany, Austria, probably also in other german speaking countries as Switzerland. Klaas and Joko Wintersheidt have a show that I love; they give each other difficult and absurd challenges in different parts of the world, just to see which of both is the “master” of the world (Joko gegen Klass - Das Duell um die Welt). They also have other very funny TV programs. Klaas was with his later wife at that occasion. She is an Austrian moderator, pretty well known also. I think I kind of interrupted them by asking him to make the foto. But I remember him smiling, kind of incredulous/amused about the situation. I suppose because people normally want to take a photo WITH him. Not him shooting the photo. After he took the photo, my cousin Andrea asked me if he was kind of famous… then I looked at him and recognized him. It was a funny, cool experience. He made a kind, down to earth impression.

I didn’t, someone I know didn’t, but my old teacher's brother’s friend did. She told me this story years ago when I still was in her class, but I remember it because I enjoyed the story so much. It was pretty simple, the person in question was just pulling out of a driveway at a local grocery store when they came across a little old lady struggling to carry her bags of food across the crosswalk. The man parked his car and walked over to her, and offered to help her with her bags. She was happy for the help and he carried them as carefully as he could. Once she was safe across the street she thanked him and was on her way. On his way back to his car he was stopped by another man who asked him if he knew who he just helped. He responded with something simple that loosely translated to fit the fact that he didn’t. He also didn’t think about it, or believe that it would matter. But then the man responded simply, “Dude, that was Rosa Parks”

I was born in Washington DC and my dad worked several high level civil service jobs before we moved south. He frequently had to do research and before the internet, there were these things called libraries where people actually went in to pull out books and do research. On Saturdays he would often go to the Library of Congress and my brother and I would tag along with our “chapter books” and sit quietly and read. One Saturday dad said he was almost done and to wait for him by the side door. It had started to rain a little and a black Cadillac pulled up and a man in a suit got out and walked briskly to the door. My brother and I saw him and opened the doors for him. He looked up and nodded. Soon dad came and we went home. The next day I was looking at the paper (the Washington Star is what we took) and I recognized the man as Sec. of Defense Robert McNamara. Maybe he was researching how to get out of Vietnam.

No, but a friend of mine did. Years ago, when I lived in NJ, a friend of mine saw an African American man helping an older limo driver with changing a tire. My friend offered to help, but both men said theyno, so he drove on. The man who helped wwith the tire would not take money from the limo driver nor his rich passenger. The following week the African American man received a notice from his bank that his mortgage had been paid in full. The passenger in the car paid it off. The passenger in the limo was a guy named Donald Trump.

Not personally, but my parents’ friends have. It was actually quite strange because it happened twice with the same guy. My parents’ friends love to snow mobile in the winter, they do it all the time at their cabin. One night, the two of them were out and they saw some random guy got his snow mobile stuck in a drift. And they decided to help him! They all had their helmets and goggles on so they all just looked the same. By the time the three of them pushed the snow mobile out of the drift, twenty minutes had passed and no one had taken off their helmets. At the end though, the man in need of help took off his helmet to greet and thank my parents’ friends. And it turned out to be Bruce Willis! He invited them over for dinner that night and they became friends. Fast forward a few years, the same thing happened again, but this time it was Bruce getting my parents’ friends out of a drift. Again, they never took off their helmets so no one saw each other. They still laugh about it to this day. So the lesson here is: always help someone who got their snow mobile stuck in the snow.

Offhandedly yes. In the 1990s Jim a friend of mine was in rehab. Jim wasn’t a close friend. He was tertiary and although I’d know him a decade or more we weren’t super close. When Jim was being released from rehab he called me and asked me for a ride from rehab home. It wasn’t a huge request and I didn’t mind giving him a ride at all it was just unusual that he called me and didn’t have someone he was closer with to ask. when I picked him up he asked if I would also drive his friend Bob from rehab somewhere. No problem. So my friend Jim introduced me to Bob and Jim is in the passenger seat and Bob in the back seat. I can plainly see Bob in my rear view mirror. I’m asking Bob about himself and what he does. He’s an actor. It’s L.A. everyone is an actor. So I figure he’s a waiter at Kate Mantilini or The Little Door because he has some presence and is good looking. LOL. I decide to be kind and humor him and ask Bob if he’d done any work I’d ever seen? I rarely go to the movies but it’s just conversation. He politely stated he’s best-known for work he’d done a in a film on Charlie Chaplin. My heart sunk. Although I experiencedn’t heard of film I noticed Bob was Robert Downey Jr.

Sort of. In the early 90s I was visiting my mom and stepdad in Nashville (TN). My mom and I were coming out of a supermarket one evening when a large bus pulled up next to us. The door opened and the driver asked for directions. I took a step inside the bus, as not to shout needlessly (truely, one of my pet peeves). As I gave the driver directions I became aware of other people on the bus. In my peripheral vision I noticed some people sitting about, in what was obviously a customized bus of some sort. All I could make out was that thier hair was long, like that of a rock band’s. The driver listened to my directions, thanked me, and shook my hand. I stepped off the bus, and the door closed behind me. The bus drive off, and I walled back to the car. My mother watched the bus as it drove off, and asked, “Who's Bon Jovi?” It was to late for me to chase them, pleading them to take me along.

This was in the late 80’s and I was working at The Warehouse music and video rental store at the time in SoCal (La Crescenta). There was this cute girl who came in the store and I spent the better part of 20 minutes helping her select a video to rent. I was totally flirting with her but didn’t even recognize her until she gave me her credit card to open an account, then I was like no way your name is Lita Ford, just like the singer??? Then she blushed and said “Kiss Me Deadly”, well no she didn’t really say that, maybe I did, hell I don’t really remember much after that moment but she was so down to earth it never made me think for a minute that she was a celebrity. Rock on Lita!!!

I worked at a pet store back in college. A coworker and I once sold a puppy to a man who looked (and sounded) very familiar, but I couldn’t quite place him. After talking to us about why he “must have this dog” (the puppy had really cool eyes, and was a breed the guy was fond of and had a few others at home already), he thanked us and off he went. Then my coworker turned to me and said, “That was Cypher”. Huh? Who?? “Have you seen The Matrix?”, he said. “That was Joe Pantoliano. He played Cypher”. It had been a few years since I’d seen the movie, so I went home and rewatched The Matrix. Sure as hell, that was the guy. Not the most Earth-shattering celebrity encounter, I guess. But I thought it was pretty cool. Every time I watch that movie with anyone, I can’t help it. They look at me like I’m nuts while I point at the screen and say “I sold him a puppy once!”.

I was working at a coffee shop in Hartford, CT, when a guy came to the counter and placed his order. I started to brew his cappuccino for his coffee drinks, and I started to chat him up, like I did with all my customers. I had many repeat customers who loved to chat back. This guy did not say much, but he was nice enough. At one point, I looked up from the cappuccino machine again and looked at his face, and I said, do you know that you look like Mark McKinney? (he was a member of the comedy troupe Kids In The Hall, appeared on Saturday Night Live for 3 seasons, and currently is on NBC’s Superstore) He replied, “I AM Mark McKinney.” I immediately told him how much I had enjoyed his work, and he said thanks. He then asked me if I was going to go to the Kids In The Hall show that night at the Oakdale Theatre, which was in Wallingford, CT. I told him no, I had to work. He replied, “Neither is anyone else.” I felt bad for him, because he was very talented and funny, but I have been an actor all over the U.S., and I know the feeling of playing to a sparsely populated house, so I could empathize. I hope at least he liked his coffee.

No. But I did hear and read about interesting stories. One story I heard was about a man who saw a woman stuck on the freeway and he stopped and changed a tire for her. She asked for his name and address and one day a brand new color TV arrived at his house. It seemed the woman he helped was Mrs. Nat King Cole. (I believe this happened after Nat was deceased.) The second story I read was about a white woman in Beverly Hills who was on an elevator with a number of black men. She was apparently very nervous and was glad to get off the elevator alive and unmolested. Some time later a big bouquet of flowers arrived in her room and she was told that her bill had been paid by someone else. One of the black men on the elevator was Eddie Murphy.

I was flying on a Virgin Airlines plan from NYC to London in the late 80s. I was in business class, and as I sat, I recognized the guy in the seat in front of me as Carlos Alomar, a session guitarist who played with a number of great front acts, and had just put out a New Age album of his own, which is how I recognized him. I talked briefly and told him I was a fan, liked his album which I owned, then another guy came up to talk to Carlos, so I let him alone. The guy who was talking to Carlos dropped his empty water cup, so I picked it up to hand it back, and looked up to see I was handing it back to David Bowie. He was cool, interested in the fact that I was an Alomar fan, and went back to First Class. I ran into him later at the bathroom, and commented on his new album “Never Let Me Down”, which he had come to NYC to do a press conference for. He acted happy that I liked it. My brush with FAME (Is it any wonder you are too cool to fool!)

Last week a famous New England Patriot’s football personality brought his entire family to my church. I was Head Usher that day. I had no idea who he was; he seemed like just a young guy with a pretty wife and a bunch of young kids coming to church. I seated them in a middle row near the back and went back to business.
