I did the collections. They put over 500 dollars in the plate. Yey. Even the smallest children dropped in 50 dollars. Yey. I hope they enjoyed their stay and our church and will come back and join the congregation.

I was taking a female friend of mine and my wife's home. I had to stop for gas. I asked if she had wanted a pop also. She said yes. Got the pop, and got in line. Paid for the pop. As I was leaving the store, a guy was walking in, & I held the door for him. As I walked to the car, I realized, I forgot to pay for gas. I walk back in and stand in line. The guy stands behind me. Finally I get to pay for gas. My friend was heading into the store to check on me. I went walking out and so did the guy, so again I heald the door for him. He stopped me and asked me directions to ssomewhere. My friend see's who I was talking to, and she freaks out, because he is her favorite NASCAR driver. I am thinking it was Dale Earnhardt Jr. But I am not sure about that, it has been a few years back.

I was an exchange student living in France. I had taken a vacation to visit a German friend and returned to the Charles DeGaulle airport several hours before my ride could pick my up. I found a side room off the large hallway to wait. A young guy my age stopped and asked if I minded him waiting in the room and I invited him in. Good looking, my age, by himself. We talked for about 3–4 hours about everything you can think of. A little flirting but nothing overt. When I saw my friends coming I said I’d have to leave, hekissed my cheek, thanked me for spending my afternoon with him giving him a chance to rest and left. I noticed a couple of guys in suits joined him. They were why no one else approached us all afternoon. When my friend saw us emerge, she was freaking out, jumping and shouting. He was the latest teen heartthrob singer. Sort of Justin Bieber at his prime type. I had no idea. Strange country, no pop music allowed in my host family. Quite an experience. Met a cute guy.

I still remember those moments when I was assigned to go to the Qingdao railway station along with other chosen pretty girls and handsome boys to welcome the arrival of the prime minister of Cambodia (柬埔寨), Norodom Sihanouk(西哈努克亲王) to visit Qingdao. It happened when I was studying in the elementary school at the end of 70’s last century when China and Cambodia had an intimate foreign relationship. He was ousted and fled to China, forming a government-in-exile to support the Khmer Rough (红色高棉), the communist party of Kampuchea supported by the North Vietnam against the kingdom of Cambodia supported by the South Vietnam. He was supported by Chinese government. Norodom Sihanouk was a celebrity of all celebrities in China at that time. The radio broadcasted his news everyday. I remember whenever I turned on the radio and listened to the news while eating my lunch or supper, the name of Norodom Sihanouk would hang around my ears again and again. It was actually the most frequent name I have ever heard from the perspective of politics. Until right now, I still don't understand whatsoever why China had so much interest in an ordinary leader of such a small country. What was the meaning of it? Anyway, I remember one day several teachers came into our classroom to look around. They were assigned by the principal to choose several of my classmates including me to take part in a rehearsal for a big event. They said it was for a leader of a nation who would arrive in our hometown to have a visit. Later, I knew it was Sihanouk who was going to come. I knew this name, but still having no idea who he was and the political meaning behind it. In the rehearsal, everyone was distributed a bunch of flowers, and we were instructed to jump a little bit higher and saying “Welcome, warm welcome, my dear Sihanouk king…”. I was assigned to the second last row since I was tall and had a general looking. But I got chosen anyway. We were brought to the Qingdao railway station to rehearse there in the field. Our school paid high attention to it and we even missed the class to do the rehearsal. You know what, eventually, Sihanouk did not come due to some reasons and I was very disappointed for it. But I actually did not realize who he was and why he came to our city, just obeying the orders of my teacher and school. I regarded it as an honor to me. Thanks for reading.

I used to work at Urban Outfitters in a quiet part of Brooklyn. Celebrities would come in from time to time (Bjork, Norah Jones, my personal favorite Michelle Williams, etc). I usually knew who they were. One day, I was ringing up customers. A lady approached me and she was very laid back in a appearance (workout gear, which was very common in that neighborhood for that time of day). I asked her if she found everything ok, she said yes. She’s not super famous, but I knew who she was as soon as I saw the name.

Does an astronaut count? I had a contract job where I was supposed to get federal labs to work with each other and domestic companies to share and/or commercialize technologies. I went around to maybe 25 labs in the 6 great lakes states and met with Technology Transfer officers to explain what our program was and try to figure out what kinds of specific technologies they had. . TT was typically a place where people were kind of put out to pasture, and while most of them were nice enough, they mostly fit the government employee stereotype. When I got to the astronaut’s lab, I noticed the receptionist was kind of surprised that I asked for him. We talked for a bit about the program, and then I asked him what he had done before, and he said he was an astronaut. I said, “No, really, what did you do?” He repeated he was an astronaut, and in a way, he seemed all the more interested that I didn't know about that until that instant.

Fairly regularly, actually.
